(29, '<p class=\"MsoNormal\">More than ten years ago, Herbert Gans argued that the general public is impacted by the choices and deeds of powerful politicians and other members of the political elite who serve as the primary sources of news. Unexpectedly, when it comes to issues affecting regular people, traditional news reports appear to mute their voices. This study notes, from preliminary investigation that news reports on Tradermoni money poverty reduction programme are not multiperspectival which has led to Nigerians to take to air their voices on Twitter, the evolving digital public sphere. Based on theory of social construction and using Norman Fairclough Critical Discourse Analysis approach, this research sets out to critically analyse twitter conversations on Tradermoni poverty programme in Nigeria. Findings from this will fill the gap in existing knowledge</p>', '10', 17, NULL, '2023-06-18 04:33:45', '2023-06-18 04:36:37', NULL),
(30, '<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-right: -2.05pt;\"><span lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size: 9.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 112%; mso-ansi-language: EN-US;\">The levels of broadcasting in Nigeria and the proliferation of broadcasting stations, all of them seeming to be in competition with one another, have implications for programming and for presentation specifically. A station&rsquo;s broadcasting, whether on radio, the blind medium, or television, the visual medium, must be strong and captivating enough for it to sustain audience attention. Broadcasting is described as the sending of messages via the medium of radio or television, with no technical control over who receives the messages. In other words, anyone with an appropriate receiver and within the transmission range can receive messages. Generally, broadcasting is considered as a veritable instrument of education, public enlightenment, entertainment, socialization and mobilization. This brings to the fore the critical role of the operators in the broadcast industry. The purpose of this paper is to give presenters in broadcasting stations in Nigeria some sense of style and correctness in their schedules as a station&rsquo;s ambassadors.</span></p>', '10', 18, NULL, '2023-10-05 14:24:31', '2023-10-05 14:29:38', NULL),
(31, '<p class=\"p2\">The levels of broadcasting in Nigeria and the proliferation of broadcasting stations, all of them seeming to be in competition with one another, have implications for programming and for presentation specifically. A station&rsquo;s broadcasting, whether on radio, the blind medium, or television, the visual medium, must be strong and captivating enough for it to sustain audience attention. Broadcasting is described as the sending of messages via the medium of radio or television, with no technical control over who receives the messages. In other words, anyone with an appropriate receiver and within the transmission range can receive messages. Generally, broadcasting is considered as a veritable instrument of education, public enlightenment, entertainment, socialization and mobilization. This brings to the fore the critical role of the operators in the broadcast industry. The purpose of this paper is to give presenters in broadcasting stations in Nigeria some sense of style and correctness in their schedules as a station&rsquo;s ambassadors.</p>', '10', 19, NULL, '2023-10-05 16:04:36', '2023-10-05 16:10:17', NULL),
