(115, '<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align: justify; line-height: normal;\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\" style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; font-family: \'Times New Roman\',serif;\">Studies have revealed that communication channels play a significant role in public campaigns. Therefore, this study assessed communication materials employed in gender awareness campaigns in the University of Ibadan. The data were juxtaposed with data gathered from interviews of nine purposively selected gender focal persons. Though the materials conveyed messages on gender discrimination, gender policy, gender equality, sexual harassment and sexual harassment policy, they are still affected by lack of personal interaction with the campaigners, cultural insensitivity to the physically challenged audience and lack of focus in terms of target audience. Besides, bureaucracy and finance are added as hindrances to effective communication. There is a need for the use of more modern interactive and participatory communication channels that are culturally sensitive to the various shades of their audience and ultimately, more commitment from the educational institution&rsquo;s authority to gender awareness campaigns.</span></p>', '3', 100, NULL, '2024-01-22 18:41:14', '2024-06-20 12:54:17', NULL),
(116, '<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align: justify; line-height: normal;\"><span lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size: 11.0pt; font-family: \'Times New Roman\',\'serif\'; mso-bidi-font-style: italic;\">The study examined the Influence of Social Media on Dressing Pattern of the students of Federal College of Education, Oyo. The study assessed the level of Social Media Use among Students of Federal College of Education Oyo. The theory employed for the study was Social Learning theory and Uses and gratification theory. The study used the descriptive survey method and the research instrument used was the Self-administered questionnaire to collect relevant information from the students. A total number of three hundred and seventy questionnaires were administered and simple random sampling technique was used to select the respondents. The data gathered was analyzed using statistical package for social sciences (SPSS) version 23 in form of tables, percentages and frequency count. The findings of the study revealed that the use of social media has succeeded in impacting the lifestyle of the students and has also influenced their dressing pattern. The study concluded that the factors influencing the use of social media among the students are the need for sense of belonging, joblessness, peer pressure and need for fun. The study recommended that fresh orientation should be conducted on the influence of social media use and how can be of benefit to the academic development of undergraduates in Nigerian universities.</span></p>', '2', 101, NULL, '2024-01-24 16:58:00', '2024-03-19 01:56:25', NULL),
(117, '<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-bottom: .0001pt; text-align: justify; line-height: normal;\"><span style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; font-family: \'Times New Roman\',\'serif\';\">Hypertension is increasingly becoming a public health challenge for the Africa continent where 46% of the populace are hypertensive and projections show that if not curtailed, the prevalence would nearly double in sub-Saharan Africa by the year 2030 and Nigeria inclusive. As deadly as this may seem, the ailment is totally preventable. The media are important allies in any public health matters as they play the role of being sources of information as well as advocates health awareness. The study aims at determining awareness of residents of Eti-Osa L. G. A on Hypertension Preventive on Channels Television: Health Matters. Quantitative survey research design was used to study 386 subjects in Eti-Osa Local Government Area. Subject selection was by multistage and purposive sampling techniques. Data was collected using self-administered semi-structures questionnaires after informed consents were obtained. The quantitative data gathered through questionnaires were analysed and coded using the Statistical Package for Social Sciences (SPSS). This study was hinged on the Agenda Setting Theory and Attitude Change Theory. Findings revealed high level of awareness on hypertension prevention messages on channels health matters among residents of Eti-Osa LGA. It was discovered that compliance levels to these messages were low. The study concludes experts should focus on understanding the way to proactively address the barriers that might negatively affect health messages. Furthermore, it recommends that clear, consistent and credible messages as well as introduction of entertainment-education are very essential for promoting compliance with hypertension preventive measures.</span></p>', '3', 102, NULL, '2024-01-24 17:02:58', '2024-06-17 17:43:12', NULL),
(118, '<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align: justify; line-height: 115%; margin: 0in 0in 12.0pt .5in;\"><span lang=\"EN\">Various metrics have been used to measure as well as understand countries&rsquo; economic prosperity and national development, however, only very few efforts have adopted aspects of communication and media content as social indicators for national development. In an attempt to shift the focus from conventional statistical metrics used as an indicator for national development, this study, through a quantitative content analysis of Independence Day presidential speeches between 2010-2022, aims to ascertain what the common themes and recurrent topics addressed in Presidential speeches in the last decade are, and how they reflect the overall well-being and economic prosperity of Nigeria as a nation. The result shows that security and safety, infrastructural development, and ethical governance and accountability are the primary themes while the least recurrent topics are education and knowledge acquisition, human capital development, social stability and inclusion, social welfare and services, and environmental sustainability. When these findings were properly placed in the context of political speeches as well as the reality in Nigeria, we conclude that Nigerians are experiencing a low quality of life and the country is experiencing below-moderate economic prosperity.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align: justify; text-indent: .5in; line-height: 200%;\">&nbsp;</p>', '1', 103, NULL, '2024-02-09 22:03:57', '2024-02-09 22:03:57', NULL),
(119, '<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align: justify; line-height: 115%; margin: 0in 0in 12.0pt .5in;\"><span lang=\"EN\">Various metrics have been used to measure as well as understand countries&rsquo; economic prosperity and national development, however, only very few efforts have adopted aspects of communication and media content as social indicators for national development. In an attempt to shift the focus from conventional statistical metrics used as an indicator for national development, this study, through a quantitative content analysis of Independence Day presidential speeches between 2010-2022, aims to ascertain what the common themes and recurrent topics addressed in Presidential speeches in the last decade are, and how they reflect the overall well-being and economic prosperity of Nigeria as a nation. The result shows that security and safety, infrastructural development, and ethical governance and accountability are the primary themes while the least recurrent topics are education and knowledge acquisition, human capital development, social stability and inclusion, social welfare and services, and environmental sustainability. When these findings were properly placed in the context of political speeches as well as the reality in Nigeria, we conclude that Nigerians are experiencing a low quality of life and the country is experiencing below-moderate economic prosperity.</span></p>', '3', 104, NULL, '2024-02-09 22:45:40', '2024-03-19 01:47:37', NULL),
(120, '<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;\"><span style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 115%; font-family: \'Times New Roman\',\'serif\';\">Abstract</span></strong></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 115%; font-family: \'Times New Roman\',\'serif\';\">Transcription and analysis of popular music is one of the hallmarks of modern musicology through which music scholars exert the vastness of their knowledge in the field to offer explanations on the musical and extra-musical features of recorded musical works with or without an initial notation by the composer/songwriter/performer as the case may be. This paper studies one of Wasiu Ayinde&rsquo;s Fuji classics &ldquo;Ara La Mo&rdquo;, presenting a musical analysis that covers the aspects of structure, melody, harmony, rhythm, scale, range and instrumentation with the aid of an initial transcription into staff notation; as well as a textual analysis that examines the language and meaning of the lyrical content. This research effort is purposed to appreciate and document the work of a Nigerian fuji music icon, with a view to document the analysis of a fuji track as an indigenous Yoruba work. It is also worthy to note that the life and musical career of Wasiu Ayinde will be briefly mentioned as an introductory to the analysis of his work. </span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align: justify;\">&nbsp;</p>', '3', 105, NULL, '2024-02-24 00:20:28', '2024-04-03 13:58:24', NULL),
