(123, 'In this paper, I have conceptualised PR and pr as metaphors that distinctively map out the boundaries between the professional and craft practice of public relations respectively. This clarification is pertinent because increasingly the lines of demarcation is becoming blurry, which emboldens charlatans to assume some sense of undeserving influence. The profession has been delegitimised by pr practitioners whose understanding of what the profession is and  does is presumably, only, about keeping the media Klieg light on organisations. This confusion has steeply resulted in an identity crisis that further deepens the misperception about the true nature of the profession. PR is about the continuous engagement between an organisation and its stakeholders based on mutual understanding and readiness to cede positions. On the contrary, pr is the subtle imposition of an organisation’s will on its stakeholders through the deployment of foul apparatuses to achieve consent through the manipulation of their cognition for compliance-gaining. Although, pr practitioners adopt some semblance of PR in their activities, it is an existential threat that must be tackled forthwith. So, for PR not to die or better still be resuscitated from its dying condition based on Robert Phillips’ submission in the book, Trust me, PR is Dead, the disaster that pr is, must be mitigated through a three-pronged approach of education, regulation, and professionalisation.', '1', 108, NULL, '2024-06-24 16:37:54', '2024-10-23 11:57:04', NULL),
(124, 'In this paper, I have conceptualised PR and pr as metaphors that distinctively map out the boundaries between the professional and craft practice of public relations respectively. This clarification is pertinent because increasingly the lines of demarcation is becoming blurry, which emboldens charlatans to assume some sense of undeserving influence. The profession has been delegitimised by pr practitioners whose understanding of what the profession is and  does is presumably, only, about keeping the media Klieg light on organisations. This confusion has steeply resulted in an identity crisis that further deepens the misperception about the true nature of the profession. PR is about the continuous engagement between an organisation and its stakeholders based on mutual understanding and readiness to cede positions. On the contrary, pr is the subtle imposition of an organisation’s will on its stakeholders through the deployment of foul apparatuses to achieve consent through the manipulation of their cognition for compliance-gaining. Although, pr practitioners adopt some semblance of PR in their activities, it is an existential threat that must be tackled forthwith. So, for PR not to die or better still be resuscitated from its dying condition based on Robert Phillips’ submission in the book, Trust me, PR is Dead, the disaster that pr is, must be mitigated through a three-pronged approach of education, regulation, and professionalisation.', '1', 109, NULL, '2024-06-24 16:41:54', '2024-06-24 16:41:54', NULL);
